		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>
<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/000052.html">Abashi - What happened to the Newbie Board?</a></B><P>

I found the Newbie Board to be a great place to ask 'dumb' questions. No one would flame and people in general were nice. It was a good forum to ask some basic advice and/or questions about the game that might not be found in an FAQ, but considered 'common knowledge' by posters in the General Forum. Why was the decision made to delete this forum?<P>

<B>We wanted to limit the number of forums based upon what we could actively moderate. Given that flames won't be tolerated here any more, this might be a good place for the questions that you mention. However, if the Newbie Zone was really enjoyed that much, we could certainly think about bringing it back.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/000096.html">why you don t fix the cannibalise 40% fizzle rate?</a></B><P>

Hello I want to know why you don't fix the cannibalise 3 spell it fizzle very near 40% of the time.<P>

<B>There's no spell-specific fizzle rate tied to that spell. Spells have an increased chance to fizzle during the level that you first become able to cast the spell. As you get at least a level higher, you should notice your ability to cast it improve greatly.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/000125.html">Question about Test and the Live Servers</a></B><P>

I'm curious... has there ever been a change in the Test server that HASN'T come to the Live Servers soon after?<P>

<B>Off the top of my head, I do recall a DOT change that was put on Test. The version that finally made the production servers was much different from the original version on test. </B><P>

I'm getting the very creepy feeling that Verant just sticks things on Test for a couple days before putting it Live, without looking at the effects it has on Test, just to cover their bums.<P>

<B>Well, I certainly couldn't say that we haven't made mistakes in the past. We do however continually try and improve our processes when we do make those mistakes.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/000135.html">Mr Wrinn? The critic is ready for your checkup now.</a></B><P>

1> As long as you continue to speak to customers with the same tone you used when dealing with these examples, players are going to remember said examples. I’ve said this before, but here’s a slightly different angle: if I said some of the things said in that FAQ, in the tone they are said, I would have been fired – immediately & without question – from any CS department I have ever worked for. And I have every reason to believe this would be true in the vastest majority of CS departments in this country. Need an example? Divine Intervention (final question under 4.1).<P>

<B>I understand what you are saying AuntieShaynta, but you'll also notice that in cases where we've tried to be extremely delicate with issues, we're usually jumped on for not giving a straight answer. Sometimes a straight answer requires that we be very blunt, and sometimes bluntness is taken with offense. In the particular case you quote, I was looking for a way to indicate that there will be no change, not "no change" in the "lets discuss it for a long time and we might change it" sense, but in the "this will never ever change" sense. There's only so many ways to state an absolute negative.</B><P>

To again quote myself, if I were in Brad’s position no quest would go live until I personally tested it. <P>

<B>While I will not deny that there is much improvement to be had in our testing department, there's certainly too many quests for Brad to test them all personally. However you are correct that someone should.</B><P>

Players are going to remember these examples as long as Verant in general and you in particular continue fertilizing their memories of these examples – by continuing the same behaviors.<P>

<B>I understand that, but I would ask that the players also take note of progress that we make. We are all people, and people make mistakes. The point that we stop learning from our mistakes is the point that you should get worried.</B><P> 

Thank you for your time.<P>

<B>And thank you for yours.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/000137.html">This is not acceptable customer service.</a></B><P>

Just happened on Brell. This is not a rant or flame for the GMs, it is a rant and flame for the technical service department who because of their lack of communication skills to the GMs cause this stuff to happen.<P>

[SNIP]<P>

<B>I certainly would have liked to see something a little more firm. I think that the GM that made the announcement had heard that they would be coming down soon, and wanted to give more than the standard 3-5 minutes notice if possible. It would be normal for the GM not to know exactly when the server would be down, though I think that they probably should have given a timeframe for what qualfied as "shortly".<P>

Concerning not being able to answer all the /tells, as much as we'd like to, we just can't. Any broadcast, regardless of content, usually results in a /tell from about 10% of the people online at the time. That's a sizeable number of /tells. The best they can do in this case is see if the same questions are being asked in a number of the /tells and try to follow up on the issue in a subsequent broadcast.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/000148.html">Threads showing as "read"</a></B><P>

<I>Hello all,<P>

I've seen a few emails and received a few posts regarding threads showing up as read before you've read them. As the boards have been reorganized, I imagine that your browser thinks that the links have been accessed on the basis of them having the same name as something you've read previously. <P>

Clearing your history through your browser should fix this up.<P>

-Gordon</I><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/000163.html">Abashi - Shaman class defining item JBB...</a></B><P>

I thought that no item was supposed to be the all defining item for that class. 
Well The Jaundice bone bracer is just that... I too am a shaman and would love to have one of these, but even from my stand point its just too powerfull...<P>

<B>Doesn't that item have a casting time on it that is great enough to the point that the item isn't "all powerful"?<P>

-Gordon</b><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

